  <p class="project-card-label">Browser Tool</p>
  <h1>motionphoto.gallery</h1>

  <p>
    motionphoto.gallery focuses on a small but useful problem: many smartphone photos contain a short video sequence, but
    that moving part is not always easy to access afterwards. The project gives users a direct way to recover and save
    that clip.
  </p>

  <p>
    The tool runs in the browser, which keeps the workflow simple. A motion photo can be opened, processed and exported
    without installing extra desktop software. For many users, that is the difference between a hidden feature they never
    use and a clip they can actually keep.
  </p>

  <p>
    Local processing is an important part of the concept. Media files do not need to be uploaded to a remote service just
    to extract the embedded video. That makes the tool especially appealing for personal recordings that users would
    rather keep on their own machine.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because the work happens inside the browser, large files can still be demanding on the device. But the tradeoff is a
    lightweight experience that removes the usual friction around motion-photo formats and makes the short video content
    much easier to reuse.
  </p>

